## Key Insights:

1. EMBODY SPANS THE CONTINUUM
   ────────────────────────────
   • Starts at pure Research Theory (Phase 1.B theoretical contributions)
   • Moves through Research Design (Phase 3.A/B synthesis work)
   • Extends into Practice Theory (Phase 3.B/4.A tool development)
   • Single project occupies multiple positions simultaneously

2. THIS IS EXPECTED AND VALUED
   ────────────────────────────
   • From the paper: "No contribution is more important than another"
   • Different positions serve different stakeholders
   • Spanning continuum = translational work

3. NOT A ONE-WAY JOURNEY
   ──────────────────────
   • The continuum shows positions, not temporal progression
   • Work doesn't "move from" RT "to" PD
   • Embody maintains all positions concurrently
   • Bidirectional: Practice insights inform theory refinement

4. NEUTRALITY ENABLES SPAN
   ────────────────────────
   • Embody's theory-neutrality allows it to serve:
     - Researchers (RT/RD needs)
     - Practitioners (PT/PD needs)
   • Same infrastructure, multiple uses
   • This is the power of Phase 4.A trading zones


## Comparison to Pasteur's Quadrant:

The TCER continuum differs from Pasteur's Quadrant:

Pasteur's Quadrant (Binary):

         High             │  Pure Basic    │  Use-Inspired
    Considerations        │   Research     │    Research
      of Use              │                │  (Pasteur's)
         Low              │  Pure Applied  │
                          └────────────────┴──────────────
                                Low    Quest for      High
                                    Fundamental Understanding


TCER Continuum (Sliding Scale):

         All four quadrants valued
         Different axes (Research/Practice vs. Understanding/Use)
         Not binary (positions are continuous, not categorical)
         Multiple simultaneous positions possible


## How Phases Map to Continuum:

┌──────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  TCER Phase      │  Typical Continuum Position                 │
├──────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Phase 1         │  RT (pure research theories)                │
│  Phase 2         │  RT, RD (theories + experimental designs)   │
│  Phase 3.A       │  RT, RD (research synthesis)                │
│  Phase 3.B       │  RD, PT (practitioner synthesis)            │
│  Phase 4.A       │  PT, (→PD) (evidence-based prototypes)      │
│  Phase 4.B       │  PT, PD (practice insights)                 │
│  Phase 5.A       │  PD (scaled interventions)                  │
│  Phase 5.B       │  PD (→back to RT) (impact analysis)         │
└──────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────────────────┘

Note: Arrows (→) indicate typical flows, but bidirectionality means
      all phases can inform all positions on the continuum.


